DS 220 Project 2¶

Data Analysis with Python Pandas (Individual) - Joshua Chang, jvc6690@psu.edu

Understanding the Dataset¶

The dataset we will be working on is taken from Kaggle.com, named "World Happiness Report." This is one of the most popular datasets in Kaggle for its good usage. This dataset contains 155 to 158 countries' happiness rank and scores, with numeric data on family, health, freedom, and more. In this project, we will analyze the World Happiness Report (WHR) for the year of 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, and 2019, to get the answers for the following points and plot the results:

  1. How has the happiness ranking of the United States changed from 2015 to 2019?
  2. How have the 10 happiest countries changed over from 2015 to 2019?
  3. How have the 10 unhappiest countries changed over from 2015 to 2019?
  4. Is there any correlation between happiness levels and Gross Domestic Product (GDP) per capita?
  5. Is there any correlation between happiness levels and life expectancy?
  6. Which factors have the strongest impact on happiness across different countries?

Data Preparation & Cleaning¶

1. Importing the dataset and python libraries¶

Before we start anything, we must import the dataset into our Jupyter Notebook file. Also, to perform data analysis on the dataset, we need pandas, NumPy, and Matplotlib. We will import all of these now, so that we can use these throughout this project.

In [1]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

data_2015 = pd.read_csv("./data/2015.csv")
data_2016 = pd.read_csv("./data/2016.csv")
data_2017 = pd.read_csv("./data/2017.csv")
data_2018 = pd.read_csv("./data/2018.csv")
data_2019 = pd.read_csv("./data/2019.csv")

2. Exploring, selecting, cleaning, and preparing the data¶

Now that we imported the dataset and python libraries, let's see what we have as a column values for each dataset.

2-e. Selecting the subset of data from the dataset¶

From 2-a, we see that there is still some inconstencies after changing the name of the columns. Now the name of the coulmns are all same but since WHA is taken from over the years, there are some fields that is in data_2015, data_2016, data_2017 but not in data_2018 and data_2019. Since we cannot create data, let us leave some columns that does not match when we are selecting the subset. The left-out coulmns will mainly be something related to std_error or dystopia_residual.

We can use DATANAME.iloc[:, [c1, c2, ..., cn]] where cn is a column index for the columns.

Here, I tried to merge all of our datasets into one dataset, which was getting too complicated to understand the table and confusing codes. Therefore, we are keeping as 5 databases.

In [32]:
'''
Selecting subset of data only for 'country', 'happiness_rank', 'happiness_score',
                                  'economy', 'family', 'life_expectancy',
                                  'freedom', 'government_corruption', 'generosity'

We are making these at the same order too, here.
'''

sub_data_2015 = data_2015.iloc[:,[0, 2, 3, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9 , 10]]
sub_data_2016 = data_2016.iloc[:,[0, 2, 3, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11]]
sub_data_2017 = data_2017.iloc[:,[0, 1, 2, 5, 6, 7, 8, 10, 9 ]]
sub_data_2018 = data_2018.iloc[:,[1, 0, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 8 , 7 ]]
sub_data_2019 = data_2019.iloc[:,[1, 0, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 8 , 7 ]]

Data Analysis¶

Now that we have all the datasets ready, we can start analysis tasks that we questioned at the beginning of the project, which are as following. We will go number by number.

  1. How has the happiness ranking of the United States changed from 2015 to 2019?
  2. How have the 10 happiest countries changed over from 2015 to 2019?
  3. How have the 10 unhappiest countries changed over from 2015 to 2019?
  4. Is there any correlation between happiness levels and Gross Domestic Product (GDP) per capita?
  5. Is there any correlation between happiness levels and life expectancy?
  6. Which factors have the strongest impact on happiness across different countries?

1. How has the happiness ranking of the United States changed from 2015 to 2019?¶

To check this, we would have to create another table that consists Year and Happiness Ranking the of United States as the columns. We can use pandas library to create the DataFrame.

In [63]:
q1 = pd.DataFrame([(2015, sub_data_2015.at['United States', 'happiness_rank']),
                   (2016, sub_data_2016.at['United States', 'happiness_rank']),
                   (2017, sub_data_2017.at['United States', 'happiness_rank']),
                   (2018, sub_data_2018.at['United States', 'happiness_rank']),
                   (2019, sub_data_2019.at['United States', 'happiness_rank']),],
                   columns = ('Year', 'Happiness Ranking of the United States'))
q1
Out[63]:
Year Happiness Ranking of the United States
0 2015 15
1 2016 13
2 2017 14
3 2018 18
4 2019 19

Now, we can make the Year values as index of the table.

In [64]:
q1.set_index('Year', inplace=True)
q1
Out[64]:
Happiness Ranking of the United States
Year
2015 15
2016 13
2017 14
2018 18
2019 19

Now that we have a dataframe with the values that we only want, we can create the visualize this dataframe with matplotlib library. A graph of the happiness ranking of the United States from 2015 to 2019 is shown below.

In [65]:
plt.plot(q1, color='Blue')
plt.grid(color='gray', linestyle='--', linewidth=1)
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.xticks([2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019])
plt.ylabel('Happiness Ranking of the United States')
plt.title('Happiness Ranking of the United States from 2015 to 2019')
plt.show()

6. Which factors have the strongest impact on happiness across different countries?¶

To see which factors impacts the happiness across different countries, we can create correlation matrix that includes all of the factors. Correlation matrix is a statistical technique used to evaluate the relationship between two variables in a dataset, so it will be good for us to compare between the variables. Also, to reduce the uncertainty here too, we will make 5 of the correlation matrix here too.

In [115]:
corr = sub_data_2015.corr()
mat = plt.matshow(corr)
plt.xticks(range(len(corr.columns)), corr.columns, rotation=90)
plt.yticks(range(len(corr.columns)), corr.columns)
plt.colorbar(mat)
plt.title('Correlation Matrix for 2015.csv', fontsize=15)
plt.show
